mlp

Class LatexMacro

  • java.lang.Object
    • mlp.LatexMacro

  • public class LatexMacro
extends java.lang.Object
    This class models LaTeX macros, that is, new user-defined LateX commands that are specified using one of the following LaTeX commands: \newcommand, \renewcommand, and \providecommand. The format of \newcommand is as follows:
    \newcommand{\name}[no-of-arguments]{definition-of-command}
    or
    \newcommand{\name}[no-of-arguments][default-1st-argument]{definition-of-command}
    where:
    • \name is the name the user-defined command/macro
    • no-of-arguments is the number of arguments (aka parameters) of this user-defined command. If the new command takes no arguments, then no-of-arguments can be set to 0 or not provided at all. In any case, this number has to be an integer between 0 and 9 inclusive.
    • definition-of-command is a (string) that defines the new command. In the definition, to make reference to the i-th argument, write #i
    • when the new command takes at least one argument, the first argument can have a default value, specified by default-1st-argument. The default value (default-1st-argument) is then used whenever the user of the new command provides (no-of-arguments - 1) actual arguments.
    The formats of \renewcommand and \providecommand are the same as that of \newcommand.

      • assignArguments

        public java.lang.String assignArguments(java.util.List<java.lang.String> argValues)
        Replaces each argument reference #i by its specified value. Two cases are distinguished:
        1. If the macro does not allow an optional 1st argument, or if it allows an optional argument but in fact a first argument is still provided: each argument reference #i is replaced by argValues.get(i-1) in the definition of the macro.
        2. If, however, the macro allows for an optional argument and the specified argument list is one less than the total number of arguments of the macro: the default first argument will be used, by inserting it at the start of the specified argument list first, and then the rest of the substitution proceeds as in the previous case.
        Parameters:
        argValues - a list of the values of the arguments in consecutive order
        Returns:
        the definition of the macro after the argument references have been replaced by the specified argument values.

      • constructMacro

        public static LatexMacro constructMacro(java.lang.String newCommand)
        Constructs a LatexMacro object from the specified "\newcommand ..." input string.
        Parameters:
        newCommand - a Latex "\newcommand" command definition. It is in the form of:
        1. \newcommand{\name}{definition}, or
        2. \newcommand{\name}[numOgArgs]{definition}, or
        3. \newcommand{\name}[numOgArgs][default1stArg]{definition}.
        Note: the braces around "\name" are optional.
        Returns:
        a LatexMacro object if the specified input is a valid new macro definition. Otherwise, it returns null.
